##How to Complete a Task - Complete Guide

Based on the steering files and hooks you now have, here's the complete workflow:

üìã Step-by-Step Task Completion Process
1. Find Your Next Task
Open the tasks file:

cat .kiro/specs/comprehensive-learning-portal/tasks.md
Look for the first unchecked task: - [ ]

Example: - [ ] 1.1.1 Initialize Maven project with Spring Boot 3.2+ and Java 21

2. Understand the Task
Read the task details:

Task description
Acceptance criteria
Requirements references (e.g., _Requirements: 1.1, 1.2_)
Check the requirements:

# Search for the requirement
grep -A 10 "Requirement 1.1" .kiro/specs/comprehensive-learning-portal/requirements.md
Check the design:

# Search for relevant design info
grep -A 10 "Maven" .kiro/specs/comprehensive-learning-portal/design.md
3. Implement the Task
Do the actual work:

Write code
Create files
Configure systems
Follow project standards (see .kiro/steering/project-standards.md)
Example for Task 1.1.1:

# Create Maven project structure
mkdir -p backend/src/main/java/com/learningportal
mkdir -p backend/src/main/resources
mkdir -p backend/src/test/java

# Create pom.xml
# (write your pom.xml with Spring Boot dependencies)
4. Test Your Implementation
Follow testing standards (see .kiro/steering/testing-standards.md):

# For backend
cd backend
mvn test

# For frontend
cd frontend
npm test
Make sure:

‚úÖ Code compiles
‚úÖ Tests pass
‚úÖ No errors
‚úÖ Meets acceptance criteria
5. Mark Task as Complete
Use the task-complete hook:

bash .kiro/hooks/task-complete.sh 1.1.1
This will:

‚úÖ Mark the task as [x] in tasks.md
‚úÖ Update progress metrics
‚úÖ Log the completion
‚úÖ Show you the next task
‚úÖ Commit the change to git
6. Run Checkpoint
Save your progress:

bash .kiro/hooks/session-checkpoint.sh
This will:

‚úÖ Commit all changes to git
‚úÖ Push to remote
‚úÖ Log the conversation
‚úÖ Generate context summary
